included.customDescription:
As part of my master's program, I worked with a remote 5-person team over a period of 3 weeks (with everyone juggling full-time jobs and other grad school classes) to tackle the problem of anxiety people face regarding others' access to their vast amount of personal data generated today.

Our team focused on the emotions surrounding the unintended viewing of personal data by a specific third-party ("creepers") and created two very well-received solutions using design thinking methodology.

included.summary:
I'm a cross-cultural qualitative UX researcher focused on making Google products more accessible for users with disabilities. Previously, I worked across product teams in Google Apps (GSuite, Classroom) on accessibility and in Localization, where I focused on delivering a native experience for the next billion users.

I'm an UX mentor at IndieBio, the world's largest seed biotech accelerator, and have a M.S. in Human Factors in Information Design. 

Prior work in China and the US include consulting for startups, advising MNCs on their China corporate communications strategies, running a lifestyle media web and print platform as chief editor, and leading country strategy for a global non-profit. 

I've led research to create a startup's MVP; designed an e-learning foundation's China strategy from the ground up to reach 7,000 kids in 1 year on zero budget; helped define stakeholder communications for a $13 billion merger; and crafted content for a social gaming startup twice featured in the Apple App Store. 

Clients ranged from two-person startups to Fortune 500s. I've collaborated with cross-functional teams across Asia-Pacific, the Americas and Europe. 

Languages: English (native), Cantonese and Mandarin (working proficiency)
Global Background: Lived in Hong Kong, New York City, Singapore, Toronto and Shanghai

Interests: underrepresented populations, healthcare, aging, education, diversity & inclusion, cross-cultural communications
